1-a)¶

Side-by-side box plots of days until failure are given in Figure 1. This graph shows that the distribution of days until failure differs substantially from one catheter brand to another. In particular, Brands A and G have larger means and larger variances than the other brands. Brands D and F seem to have both the smallest mean and the smallest variance. In general, there is a tendency for catheter brands with large means to also have large variances. This phenomenon, variance that increases with the mean, is a common form of heteroscedasticity.

* Part b: Fit one-way anova model, test equality of population means, and
          test homogeneity of variance.; 

ods graphics off; ods trace on;
proc glm data=assay;
title 'One-way anova in PROC GLM analyzing days until failure';
title2 'for seven catheter brands';
  class cathname;
  model days=cathname/ss3; * Type 1 and 3 F tests are same in one-way model so
                             here the ss3 option asks for just the Type 3 tests, 
                             which suppresses the Type 1 tests and eliminates 
                             redundant output;
  means cathname/hovtest=bf;
  means cathname/hovtest=levene(type=abs);
  means cathname/hovtest=levene(type=square);
  ods exclude means#2 means#3; *This suppresses 2 of the three identical tables of 
                                sample means that were generated by having three
                                MEANS statements in this code;
run;

1-b)¶

Next, we analyze days until failure with a one-way anova model and conduct the F test of equal means for the 7 catheter brands. This is done in PROC ANOVA and the F test is given below in Table 1. The test statistic’s value is F=18.14 on 6 numerator degrees of freedom (df) and 69 denominator df, and yields p-value less than 0.0001. Based on this test result, we reject the hypothesis of equal means for the 7 catheter brands and conclude that at least one pair of catheter brands differs in terms of the mean days until failure. However, this test was computed under the usual assumptions of the analysis of variance, which includes an assumption of constanat variance within all treatment groups. Therefore we also conduct homogeneity of variance (HOV) tests. Results of three such HOV tests are given in Tables 2, 3, and 4. All three tests yield the same conclusion that the variance is not constant across the seven catheter brands in this data set. This conclusion is consistent with our observations from part a, and should lead us to conduct an alternative analysis that either allows non-constant variance (such as Welch’s weighted anova F test), or where the response variable has been transformed so that, after transformation, the homogeneity of variance assumption holds (see part e).

In [4]:
* Part c: Now compute the HOV tests by doing the anova F test on some constructed 
          variables;

* Compute the mean and median by catheter brand and merge them back in with the
  original data;          
proc means data=assay noprint;
  by cathname;
  var days;
  output out=cathout mean(days)=mndays median(days)=meddays;
run;
data assay2;
  merge assay cathout;
    by cathname;
  * Now compute the constructed variables we need for the HOV tests.
    That is, compute the absolute deviations from the catheter means, 
    the squared deviations from the catheter means, and the absolute deviations
    from the catheter medians.;
  devmean=abs(days-mndays);
  devmean2=(days-mndays)**2;
  devmed=abs(days-meddays);
  * Also compute the log-transformed response that we will need for part d;
  logdays=log(days+1);
  label logdays="Log(days until failure +1)" cathname="Catheter brand"
    devmean="Abs deviation from trt mean"
    devmed="Abs deviation from trt median"
    devmean2="Sq deviation from trt mean";
run;
ods graphics off;
title 'BF test using anova F test on a constructed variable';
title2;
proc glm data=assay2;
  class cathname;
  model devmed=cathname/ss3;
  ods select none;
  ods select modelanova; * suppress all output except the F test that we want;
run;
title 'Levene (abs) test using anova F test on a constructed variable';
proc glm data=assay2;
  class cathname;
  model devmean=cathname/ss3;
  ods select none;
  ods select modelanova; * suppress all output except the F test that we want;
run;
title 'Levene (square) test using anova F test on a constructed variable';
proc glm data=assay2;
  class cathname;
  model devmean2=cathname/ss3;
  ods select none;
  ods select modelanova; * suppress all output except the F test that we want;
run;

1-d)¶

After transforming the response variable, the F test of equal means is shown in Table 8. This test (F6,69=14.52, p<.0001) is highly significant, so our conclusion remains as in part b; the mean days until failure is not the same for the 7 catheter brands. The HOV tests on the transformed response are given in Tables 9, 10 and 11. These tests are not significant (e.g., for the Brown-Forsyth test we have F6,63=0.95, p=0.4666), so we fail to conclude that the variance differs across catheter brands. Thus, after transformation, there is little reason to doubt the homogeneity of variance assumption, and we now have faith in our test result regarding equality of the mean response across catheter brand.

* Part a;

* Generate 1000 data sets, each with 40 observations (20 obs in each
  of two treatments) and 10 correlated response variables y1-y10;
data sim;
  call streaminit(2423);
  array resp(10) y1-y10;
  array mn(10) mu1-mu10 (10 20 30 40 50 5 15 25 35 45);
  do dset=1 to 1000;
    do i=1 to 40;
      trt=(i>20)+1;
      bi=rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(7));
      do j=1 to 10;
           resp(j)=mn(j)+bi+rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(3));
        end;
      output;
    end;
  end;
run;

* Now verify the distributions that Y1-Y10 were generated to have;
ODS GRAPHICS OFF;
title 'Summary statistics on Y1-Y10 and pairwise correlations among them';
title2 'using all 40,000 observations as a single data set';
proc corr data=sim ;
  var y1-y10;
run;

2-a)¶

After generating 1000 data sets, each with a sample size of 40 and with variables as described in the project assignment sheet, I computed summary statistics and a correlation matrix on all variables from the combined 40000-observation data set. The results appear in Tables 12 (univariate summary statistics) and 13 (correlations). The sample means are all close to the population values that they were generated from. The variables all have sample standard deviation that is very close to the population SD of The pair-wise sample correlations among Y1-Y10 are all quite close to the population correlation of 0.70 that was used to generate the data.

* part b;


%macro ODSOff(); /* Call prior to BY-group processing */
ods graphics off;
ods exclude all;
ods noresults;
%mend;

%macro ODSOn(); /* Call after BY-group processing */
ods graphics on;
ods exclude none;
ods results;
%mend;

%let NumSamples = 1000;            /* number of samples */

data PowerSizeSim(drop=i Delta);
call streaminit(2423);
mu1=10;mu2=20;mu3=30;mu4=40;mu5=50;mu6=5;mu7=15;mu8=25;mu9=35;mu10=45;

do N =  20;/* sample size                   */
   do SampleID = 1 to &NumSamples;
      do i = 1 to N;
         trt = 1; 

            bi=rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(7));
            Y1=mu1+bi+rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(3));
            Y2=mu2+bi+rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(3));
            Y3=mu3+bi+rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(3));
            Y4=mu4+bi+rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(3));
            Y5=mu5+bi+rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(3));
            Y6=mu6+bi+rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(3));
            Y7=mu7+bi+rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(3));
            Y8=mu8+bi+rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(3));
            Y9=mu9+bi+rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(3));
            Y10=mu10+bi+rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(3));
            output;
         trt = 2; 

            bi=rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(7));
            Y1=mu1+bi+rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(3));
            Y2=mu2+bi+rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(3));
            Y3=mu3+bi+rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(3));
            Y4=mu4+bi+rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(3));
            Y5=mu5+bi+rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(3));
            Y6=mu6+bi+rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(3));
            Y7=mu7+bi+rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(3));
            Y8=mu8+bi+rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(3));
            Y9=mu9+bi+rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(3));
            Y10=mu10+bi+rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(3));
         output;
      end;
   end;
end;
drop mu1-mu10;
run;

proc print data=powersizesim(obs=50);
run;


/* 2. Compute statistics */
%ODSOff 
proc ttest data=PowerSizeSim; 
   by N SampleID; 
   class trt; 
   var y1-y10; 
   ods output ttests=TTests(where=(method="Pooled")); 
run; 
proc print data=ttests(obs=100);
run;
%ODSOn 

 

/* 3. Construct indicator var for obs that reject H0 */ 
data ResultsSize; 
set TTests; 
RejectH0 = (Probt <= 0.05); 
run; 

data want;
set ResultsSize;
cumH0+RejectH0;
run;


proc means data=ResultsSize noprint;
  var RejectH0;
  output out=alb_stats sum(RejectH0)=totalH0;
run;

proc print data=ResultsSize(obs=100);
run;

proc means data=ResultsSize noprint nway ;
class SampleID;
var RejectH0;
output out=data2 mean=RejectH0_mean;
run;
proc print data=data2(obs=100);
run;


proc report data=ResultsSize headline headskip;
  title1 "(Type 1 error Analysis)";
  column  SampleID RejectH0 RejectH0=mean_RejectH0 RejectH0=pctValue;
  define SampleID / group 'Dataset';
  define RejectH0 / analysis sum format=6. width=10 'Sum of RejectH0';
  
  define mean_RejectH0 / analysis mean format=6.2 width=10 'Avg # of Significants';
       
  define pctValue / analysis PCTSUM format=8.3 'Percentage';
run;
  


proc freq data=ResultsSize; 
   by N; 
   tables RejectH0 / out=SimPower(where=(RejectH0=1));
run;

2-b)¶

T tests were performed for each variable and each data set using a single call to PROC TTEST. The test results were saved to an output data set using the ODS OUTPUT statement. From that output data set, only the results from the pooled variance tests were retained, and I created variables NSIG and ANYSIG which, respectively, counted the number of significant results per data set and recorded whether or not there was at least one significant result for each data set. Means of these two variables are reported in Table 14. From these results we see that the average number of significant test results when performing 10 t tests per data set is 0.486, and the proportion of data sets for which at least one significant result was obtained (i.e., for which at least one Type I error was made) is 0.227 or 22.7%. This shows the multiple comparison problem fairly dramatically. The message is that if we are not careful to avoid analyzing more response variable than necessary and/or to use a statistical methodology that controls the combined Type I error rate, then we are likely to find spurious results very often (on the order of 22.7% of the time according to the simulation scenario used here) by chance alone. No wonder there are many scientific findings that cannot be replicated!

%let NumSamples = 500;
data Gen500(drop=i);
call streaminit(2423);
beta0=1; beta1=1; beta2=1; beta3=1;
mu1=10;mu2=20;mu3=30;mu4=40;mu5=50;mu6=5;mu7=15;mu8=25;mu9=35;mu10=45;

do N =  100;
   do SampleID = 1 to &NumSamples;
      do i = 1 to N;
         trt = 1; 

            bi=rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(7));
            X1=mu1+bi+rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(3));
            X2=mu2+bi+rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(3));
            X3=mu3+bi+rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(3));
            X4=mu4+bi+rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(3));
            X5=mu5+bi+rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(3));
            X6=mu6+bi+rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(10));
            X7=mu7+bi+rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(10));
            X8=mu8+bi+rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(10));
            X9=mu9+bi+rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(10));
            X10=mu10+bi+rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(10));
            X11=ranpoi(2423,6);
            X12=10*ranuni(2423);

            noise=rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(9));

             output;

* part b;


%macro ODSOff(); /* Call prior to BY-group processing */
ods graphics off;
ods exclude all;
ods noresults;
%mend;

%macro ODSOn(); /* Call after BY-group processing */
ods graphics on;
ods exclude none;
ods results;
%mend;


%ODSOff
proc reg data=Gen500 plots=(criteria sbc) outest=est1;
      by SampleID;
            Forward: model Y=X1-X13 / slstay=0.05 slentry=0.05
            selection=forward details=summary;
            Backward: model Y=X1-X13 / slstay=0.05 slentry=0.05
            selection=backward details=summary;
            Stepwise: model Y=X1-X13 / slstay=0.05 slentry=0.05
            selection=stepwise details=summary;
   run;
%ODSOn

data new;
    set est1;
    NumberIn=13-nmiss(of X1-X13);
    rename _MODEL_= Method;
    run;

title 'Number of variables in model for 3 selection methods';
proc print data=new(obs=50);run;

proc freq data=new;
    tables Method*NumberIn / nocol nopercent;
    run;

title 'Number of variables in model for 3 selection methods';
proc sgpanel data=new;
 panelby Method / columns=3 rows=1;
 histogram NumberIn / nbins=10 binstart=1 binwidth=1 scale=count datalabel;
run;

3-b)¶

I fit regression models using each selection method to each data set using a single call to PROC REG. I then saved the SelectionSummary table as an output data set, which I processed with additional SAS code to retain only observations from the last step of the selection algorithm for each algorithm and data set. From those observations I determined obtained a two-way contingency table cross-classifying the selection method by the number of variablels chosen for the model. Results appear in Table 18. The three methods performed very similarly. All methods chose the right number of variables to include in the model (although we don’t know whether they picked the right set of three variables) about 60-61% of the time and picked too many variables about 38-39% of the time. Of course the most common mistake was picking one too many variables (4 instead of 3), but choosing 5 or more variables into the model was not terribly rate (about 7-9% of the time, depending on method).

call streaminit(8956);
do N =  5;/* sample size                   */
   do SampleID = 1 to &NumSamples;
      do trt = 1 to N;
            Y1=100+rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(9));
            Y2=100+rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(9));
            Y3=100+rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(9));
            Y4=100+rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(9));
            Y5=100+rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(9));
            Y6=100+rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(9));
            Y7=100+rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(9));
            Y8=100+rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(9));
            Y9=100+rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(9));
            Y10=100+rand('NORMAL',0,sqrt(9));
            avg_y=(sum(of Y1-Y10))/10;
             output;
      end;
   end;
end;
*drop Y1-Y10;
run;

proc print data=PowerSizeSim(obs=100);run;



%ODSOff 
proc glm data=PowerSizeSim;
  class SampleID trt;
  model Y1-Y10=trt;
  lsmeans trt/pdiff cl adjust=t alpha=0.05;
  ods output lsmeandiffcl=mndiffs;
run;
quit;
